summary: I’m an adult and I love the Avengers Assemble cartoon
body:
I’m an adult and I love the Avengers Assemble cartoon

My only complain with it is that Iron Man’s capabilities vary wildly from episode to episode.

One ep he is incredibly powerful and the next he’s their slow weakling leader that is always saved by their teammates and while that in itself is not bad, he’s rarely the one doing the saving.

Also I wonder constantly just how rich Tony has to be to pay for the daily damage to the tower.

summary: It wasn’t what Tony expected when he heard Peter’s scream from the lab. He had stepped out for a couple moments, to the vending...
body:
It wasn’t what Tony expected when he heard Peter’s scream from the lab. He had stepped out for a couple moments, to the vending machine just outside, to grab something to eat real quick, so Peter would stop nagging him, when it happened. 

Peter’s scream came suddenly, causing Tony to drop the back of pretzels he had grabbed, leaving them forgotten as he ran back into the lab, hand over his chest to assess the threat, simply to find Peter on the ceiling, and no sign of any threat that Tony could perceive. 

He stopped, frowning, glancing up at the teen still on the ceiling as he crawled across it to drop down behind Tony, eyes darting around. 

“Kid? What happened?” Tony kept his hand over his chest, ready to call the suit forward any moment, and Peter blinked, realizing just how protective Tony was getting. 

“There… There’s no one here. Spidey Sense would’ve warned me, I just… I guess I didn’t perceive it as a threat… Which means it’s not venomous…” he mumbled, peeking around Tony carefully. 

“What isn’t venomous?” 

Peter turned red, looking away nervously. “There’s… There’s a spider on my desk.” 

Tony was quiet a moment, before carefully walking over to Peter’s desk. True to his word, a small house spider skittered across it to duck under some paper that Peter had left. Tony raised an eyebrow, grabbing the empty water cup Peter had been using, moving the paper to trap the spider under it, before slipping a paper underneath and walking it carefully to the balcony where he placed it on the ledge and freed it. Peter watched quietly as he did this, before carefully moving back to his desk to inspect it himself, making sure it was free of any arachnid threats. 

He looked a little guilty as Tony walked back in, but Tony didn’t seem to really mind, setting the paper back down and throwing the plastic cup away, shaking his head a bit. “C’mon kid. You scared me.” 

“Sorry Mr. Stark… it startled me is all.” 

“You’d think nothing could startle you with that magic sixth sense of yours. Just… try not to scream like that next time? I left my pretzels out there.” 

Peter smiled softly, nodding a bit. “Alright… Thank you Mr. Stark…” 

“I’m never gonna get you to call me Tony, am I?” 

“Nope.”

title: shoulders
body:
read it on the AO3 at http://bit.ly/2Txh1Se

by WhimsicalEthnographies

“She’s smart,” Peter takes a breath. “Someone else smart once told me that sometimes after a bad dream, you feel better if you tell someone about it…”

Mr. Stark huffs. “I’ll accept you trying to make me feel better if I have to, but I draw the line at you being my psychiatrist. That is a burden you will not shoulder.”

“Mr. Stark,” Peter’s not stupid, he knows Mr. Stark doesn’t want to talk about it, because he never wants to talk about his nightmares either, but he knows he always feels better when he does. And he knows he only does when Mr. Stark or May refuse to leave until he starts talking. “‘When you talk about it, it’s less real,’ or something like that.”

“Why do you only remember what I say when you can use it against me?”

“Because I’m a teenager,” Peter leans into him a little.
